Insights:

  • If anyone has an EnvironemntSatisfaction is very high then they probably leave the job.
  • The Research & Development has the highest attrition, followed by Sales department. Human Resources has the lowest attrition.
  • Employees with a bachelor's degree show higher attrition rates than those with other educational backgrounds.
  • Employees in the Life Sciences and Medical fields show higher attrition rates compared to other fields.
  • Employees with low environment satisfaction have higher attrition rates. Those with very high satisfaction have the lowest attrition.
  • Both male and female employees show similar attrition patterns, with males having slightly higher attrition.
  • Sales Representatives have the highest attrition, while Research Directors and Laboratory Technicians have lower attrition rates.
  • Employees with low job satisfaction have significantly higher attrition rates.
  • Single employees have higher attrition rates compared to married and divorced employees.
  • Employees who work overtime show a significantly higher attrition rate compared to those who do not.
  • Employees with an "Excellent" performance rating have higher attrition rates than those rated as Outstanding.
  • Employees with better work-life balance have higher attrition rates compared to those with bad work-life balance.

Final conclusions:¶

Department:¶
  • Conclusion: The Research & Development department exhibits a higher attrition rate compared to Sales and Human Resources. This suggests a need for targeted retention strategies within Research & Development to address specific challenges faced by employees in this department.
Business Travel:¶
  • Conclusion: Employees who travel rarely have higher attrition rates compared to those who travel frequently or not at all. This indicates that employees who occasionally travel may face unique stressors or dissatisfaction. Organizations should explore ways to better support these employees.
Environment Satisfaction:¶
  • Conclusion: Employees with low environment satisfaction have the highest attrition rates. To reduce turnover, organizations should focus on improving the overall work environment, ensuring it is conducive to employee satisfaction and well-being.
Job Involvement:¶
  • Conclusion: Employees with low job satisfaction have significantly higher attrition rates. Addressing factors that contribute to job dissatisfaction, such as workload, career progression, and recognition, is crucial for reducing attrition.
Job Satisfaction:¶
  • Conclusion: Employees who travel rarely have higher attrition rates compared to those who travel frequently or not at all. This indicates that employees who occasionally travel may face unique stressors or dissatisfaction. Organizations should explore ways to better support these employees.
Over Time:¶
  • Conclusion: Employees who work overtime exhibit higher attrition rates. It is important for organizations to manage overtime effectively and promote a healthy work-life balance to prevent burnout and retain employees.
Marital Status:¶
  • Conclusion: Single employees have higher attrition rates compared to married and divorced employees. This suggests that single employees might have different work-life balance needs or engagement levels that should be addressed to improve retention.

By retaining outliers, we ensure that our analysis captures the complete picture, allowing for more insightful interpretations and more robust modeling outcomes.

In [80]:
def get_train_report(model, X_train, y_train):
    # Make predictions on training data
    y_train_pred = model.predict(X_train)
    
    # Generate classification report
    train_report = classification_report(y_train, y_train_pred)
    
    # Generate confusion matrix
    conf_matrix_train = confusion_matrix(y_train, y_train_pred)
    
    # Calculate training accuracy
    accuracy_train = accuracy_score(y_train, y_train_pred)
    
    return train_report, conf_matrix_train, accuracy_train
In [81]:
def get_test_report(model, X_test, y_test):
    # Make predictions on test data
    y_test_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    
    # Generate classification report
    test_report = classification_report(y_test, y_test_pred)
    
    # Generate confusion matrix
    conf_matrix_test = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_test_pred)
    
    # Calculate test accuracy
    accuracy_test = accuracy_score(y_test, y_test_pred)
    
    return test_report, conf_matrix_test, accuracy_test

Over-fitting in Decision Tree¶

The decision tree is said to be over-fitted if it tries to perfectly fit all the observations in the training data. We can calculate the difference between the train and test accuracy to identify if there is over-fitting.

Tune the Hyperparameters using GridSearchCV (Decision Tree)¶

In [65]:
tuned_paramaters = [{'criterion': ['entropy', 'gini'], 
                     'max_depth': range(2, 10),
                     'max_features': ["sqrt", "log2"],
                     'min_samples_split': range(2,10),
                     'min_samples_leaf': range(1,10),
                     'max_leaf_nodes': range(1, 10)}]
 
# instantiate the 'DecisionTreeClassifier' 
# pass the 'random_state' to obtain the same samples for each time you run the code
decision_tree_classification = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state = 10)

# use GridSearchCV() to find the optimal value of the hyperparameters
# estimator: pass the decision tree classifier model
# param_grid: pass the list 'tuned_parameters'
# cv: number of folds in k-fold i.e. here cv = 5
tree_grid = GridSearchCV(estimator = decision_tree_classification, 
                         param_grid = tuned_paramaters, 
                         cv = 5)

# fit the model on X_train and y_train using fit()
tree_grid_model = tree_grid.fit(X_train, y_train)

# get the best parameters
print('Best parameters for decision tree classifier: ', tree_grid_model.best_params_, '\n')

In [252]:
def plot_confusion_matrix(model):
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    
    # create a confusion matrix
    # pass the actual and predicted target values to the confusion_matrix()
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)

    # label the confusion matrix  
    # pass the matrix as 'data'
    # pass the required column names to the parameter, 'columns'
    # pass the required row names to the parameter, 'index'
    conf_matrix = pd.DataFrame(data = cm,columns = ['Predicted:0','Predicted:1'], index = ['Actual:0','Actual:1'])

    # plot a heatmap to visualize the confusion matrix
    # 'annot' prints the value of each grid 
    # 'fmt = d' returns the integer value in each grid
    # 'cmap' assigns color to each grid
    # as we do not require different colors for each grid in the heatmap,
    # use 'ListedColormap' to assign the specified color to the grid
    # 'cbar = False' will not return the color bar to the right side of the heatmap
    # 'linewidths' assigns the width to the line that divides each grid
    # 'annot_kws = {'size':25})' assigns the font size of the annotated text 
    sns.heatmap(conf_matrix, annot = True, fmt = 'd', cmap = ListedColormap(['lightskyblue']), cbar = False, 
                linewidths = 0.1, annot_kws = {'size':25})

    # set the font size of x-axis ticks using 'fontsize'
    plt.xticks(fontsize = 20)

    # set the font size of y-axis ticks using 'fontsize'
    plt.yticks(fontsize = 20)

    # display the plot
    plt.show()
In [253]:
def plot_roc(model):
    y_pred_prob = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
    
    # the roc_curve() returns the values for false positive rate, true positive rate and threshold
    # pass the actual target values and predicted probabilities to the function
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred_prob)

    # plot the ROC curve
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr)

    # set limits for x and y axes
    plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
    plt.ylim([0.0, 1.0])

    # plot the straight line showing worst prediction for the model
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1],'r--')

    # add plot and axes labels
    # set text size using 'fontsize'
    plt.title('ROC curve for Admission Prediction Classifier', fontsize = 15)
    plt.xlabel('False positive rate (1-Specificity)', fontsize = 15)
    plt.ylabel('True positive rate (Sensitivity)', fontsize = 15)

    # add the AUC score to the plot
    # 'x' and 'y' gives position of the text
    # 's' is the text 
    # use round() to round-off the AUC score upto 4 digits
    plt.text(x = 0.82, y = 0.3, s = ('AUC Score:',round(roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_prob),4)))

    # plot the grid
    plt.grid(True)

AdaBoost Model Outperforms for Classification Task¶

Based on the test data accuracy and classification report, it's evident that the AdaBoost model outperforms the other models with an accuracy of 0.8641. Here's a comprehensive conclusion based on the provided results:

  1. Model Selection: The AdaBoost model with an accuracy of 0.8641 demonstrates superior performance compared to other models, making it the preferred choice for this classification task.

  2. Accuracy Comparison: AdaBoost achieved the highest test data accuracy among all models, indicating its effectiveness in predicting the target variable.

  3. Precision and Recall: AdaBoost shows balanced precision and recall values for both classes ('No' and 'Yes'). It achieved a precision of 0.88 for class 'No' and 0.67 for class 'Yes', indicating its ability to correctly identify positive and negative cases. Similarly, AdaBoost achieved a recall of 0.97 for class 'No' and 0.33 for class 'Yes', suggesting its capability to capture true positive instances.

  4. F1-Score: The F1-score for AdaBoost is 0.92 for class 'No' and 0.44 for class 'Yes'. While the F1-score considers both precision and recall, it provides a balanced measure of a model's performance across classes. AdaBoost demonstrates a strong F1-score for class 'No' and a moderate F1-score for class 'Yes'.

  5. Overall Performance: The AdaBoost model exhibits robust performance across various evaluation metrics, making it suitable for the classification task at hand. Its high accuracy, balanced precision and recall, and strong F1-scores make it a reliable choice for predicting the target variable.

Unlocking Employee Retention: Insights and Strategies for Sustainable Workforce Management¶

Salary and Compensation Analysis:

Monthly income, daily rate, and hourly rate are important predictors of attrition. Analyze the salary structure and compensation packages offered by the company. Conduct a comparative analysis with industry standards to ensure that the company's salary levels are competitive and attractive enough to retain employees.

Training and Development Programs:

Employees who received more training in the past year are less likely to leave. Evaluate the effectiveness of existing training programs and initiatives. Invest in continuous learning and development opportunities to enhance employee skills and competencies, which can contribute to higher job satisfaction and retention.

Employee Tenure and Experience:

Total working years and the number of companies worked can provide insights into employee stability and turnover trends. Identify factors that influence long-term retention and career progression within the company, such as mentorship programs, promotion opportunities, and employee engagement initiatives.

Work-Life Balance and Overtime Management:

Employees who work overtime may be at risk of burnout and dissatisfaction. Assess the impact of overtime hours on employee well-being and productivity. Implement strategies to promote work-life balance, such as flexible work arrangements, time-off policies, and workload distribution strategies.

Exit Interviews and Feedback Mechanisms:

Conduct exit interviews with departing employees to understand the reasons for attrition and gather feedback on areas for improvement. Use employee surveys and feedback mechanisms to continuously monitor employee satisfaction and identify potential issues before they escalate into attrition.
